Introduction[edit]

This Verification Assets page acts as a centrally aggregated source of important information useful to those who would like to verify the historical integrity of the Whonix operating system, including versions under past project names "TorBOX" and "aos".

Note: The information provided on this page may not be entirely comprehensive. Despite best efforts, there are likely to be instances of information that have been mistakenly left out or that have been previously removed from the internet without remaining archival evidence.

Note: The information provided on this page is not meant to be an official substitute for original sources. You should verify any information you use on this page with original sources. Where available, permanent archives of original sources have been captured with reputable third-party archiving sites and linked from this page. Note that any version of original source information may have theoretically been changed or modified between instances of original publishing and permanent archiving. Please consider checking and comparing all relevant date/time stamps of any information you make use of, including the revision history of this page.

Note: The primary developer of Whonix, Patrick Schleizer, was originally an anonymous developer of the project who used pseudonyms (originally "proper" and subsequently "adrelanos") for his identity, before the public unveiling of his real life identity in January 2014. [1] An effort has been made on this page to note if a source of information was originally published under a pseudonym of Patrick Schleizer, as "proper" or "adrelanos".

Note: In some cases, known alternate URLs exist for a site, which may have contained differing content, and have been provided under the Archive URL column with differentiating letters (A, B, C, etc).

Whonix Signing Keys[edit]

Here are the cryptographic keys that have been used in the signing of Whonix operating system releases.

Note: In the Whonix Versions section below, signed versions of the operating system will identify and link back to the unique Whonix Signing Key which was used for that version's signatures.

Note: According to Patrick Schleizer, the first version of the operating system to be signed was Whonix 0.4.5. [2] [3]

Note: Patrick Schleizer has documented his OpenPGP key transition between Whonix Signing Key #1 and Whonix Signing Key #2 with the following posts: here, here, here. [4] [5] [6]
